<F P=100> Economic &amp; Agricultural </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Roundup' Views Agricultural Development Program </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1903162094 Beijing XINHUA in English 1245 GMT 19 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1903162094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Roundup: How China's Farm Yields Are Raised" -- XINHUA </F>
headline] 
  [Text] Beijing, March 19 (XINHUA) -- An overall 
agricultural development program across China has paid off 
through a decade of practice. 
  Advocated by the Chinese Government since the late 1980s, 
the 
program has focused on building water conservancy projects, 
introducing new and advanced agro-techniques, setting up 
commodity grain production and animal-breeding centres and 
training farmers technically. 
  "It has proved a successful way to rejuvenate China's 
agriculture," a government official in charge of agriculture 
said. 
  With the program, according to a recent survey, China has 
transformed 7.33 million hectares of low-yield farmland into 
high- yield land, reclaimed more than one million hectares of 
waste land, planted trees on 1.04 million hectares, and improved 
306,000 hectares of grassland over the past decade and more. 
  As a result, it has obtained 17.16 billion additional 
kilograms of grain, 2.52 million kilograms of cotton, 700,000 
tons of oil- bearing crops, 9.77 million kilograms of sugar and 
620,000 tons of meat. 
  Farmers in areas included in the program have earned 200 
yuan 
extra per capita a year. 
  One example is the Huanghuaihai Plains, which covers the 
valleys between the Yellow, Huaihe and Haihe rivers in part of 
Anhui, Hebei and Shandong provinces. In the past this area was 
frequently hit by natural disasters. By introducing the overall 
agricultural development measures, farmers have transformed 
3.368 million hectares of low-yield fields into high-yield 
farmland, improved water irrigation facilities and introduced 
new farm varieties and scientific farming through five years of 
hard efforts. 
  The grain output in the plains area of Shandong and Hebei 
Provinces now accounts for 33 percent of the provinces' total 
and that in Anhui for 65 percent. 
  Known as a granary, the Northeast China Plain has increased 
its grain output between 2,250 kilograms and 3,000 kilograms per 
hectare as a result of employing scientific farming methods and 
transformation of the lower-yield land. 
  Liaoning Province in northeast China is a key industrial 
centre, which used to buy at least 1.5 billion kilograms of 
grain every year from other parts of the country to feed its 
population. 
  The overall agricultural development has helped this 
province 
to become self-sufficient in grain and non-staple food over the 
past five years. 
  East China has more people with less farmland. 
  With farmland averaging only 0.04 hectares per capita, the 
coastal Zhejiang Province has dammed tidal land to use as 
farmland to boost its grain output over the past five years. 
  Western China, which has adverse natural conditions, has 
built a number of farm capital projects to improve the 
ecological environment. 
  Sichuan Province has improved and expanded irrigation 
facilities; Guizhou and Yunnan provinces built terraced fields; 
the Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region constructed water pumping 
projects to help transform its poor land; and the Inner Mongolia 
Autonomous Region upgraded its grassland. 
  In addition, all the areas involved have studied 
agro-techniques. 
  One example is the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region, which 
has earned 7.5 million U.S. dollars by exporting a new variety 
of grape. 
  Anhui, Jiangsu and Zhejiang Provinces in the middle and 
lower 
reaches of the Chang Jiang River, have applied more than 3,000 
new techniques and fine varieties to farming in recent years. 
  Training courses and technical schools for farmers are 
mushrooming across the country. 
  A survey shows that China still has 60 million hectares of 
low- yield farmland, 300 million hectares of low-yield 
grassland, 828,000 hectares of low-lying coastal land and 67 
million hectares of sandy wasteland, which are ripe for 
transformation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

