<F P=100> Southwest Region </F>
<H3> <TI>   Major Highways Upgraded in Tibet </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2203074894 Beijing XINHUA in English 0647 GMT 22 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2203074894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Lhasa, March 22 (XINHUA) -- Much headway has been 
made in the improvement of three major highways in the Tibet 
Autonomous Region in southwest China. 
  The highways link the region with Qinghai and Sichuan 
Provinces and Nepal, respectively. 
  The construction of the Heihe-Gamdo Highway has been 
completed, and work is going well on some sections of the 
China-Nepal Highway, upgrading projects on the Qinghai-Tibet and 
Sichuan-Tibet Highways, and the Lhaze Bridge. 
  Highways in Tibet are subject to frozen earth, mud-rock 
flows, snowslides, snow storms, desertification and landslides. 
  Statistics show that such natural disasters have blocked 
highways in Tibet for an average of over 100 days each year in 
the past over 40 years. 
  The Qinghai-Tibet Highway has undergone three large-scale 
improvements. 
  As Tibet is the only region with no railway outlets, the 
Chinese Government attaches great importance to highway 
construction. 
  In the past 40 years the central government has invested 
over 
4 billion yuan (almost 500 million U.S. dollars at the current 
exchange rate) in highway construction. 
  The upgrading and improvement of the Qinghai-Tibet Highway 
started in 1992 and will cost 850 million yuan (about 100 
million U.S. dollars). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-3951 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi057_q_94008" </HT>


