<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Ministry Holds Weekly News Briefing </TI></H3>
<H4>   Comments on Korean Nuclear Issue </H4>
<F P=102> OW2403094794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0834 GMT 24 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2403094794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 24 KYODO -- China renewed Thursday 
[24 March] its calls for dialogue to solve the nuclear question 
on the Korean peninsula as tensions continued to mount under 
sharpened warlike rhetoric between North and South Korea. 
  "The reason we stand for seeking a solution through dialogue 
is that we believe this issue can be solved through it," a 
Foreign Ministry spokesman said. 
  Spokesman Wu Jianmin told journalists at his weekly 
briefing, 
"We oppose exerting pressure as this will only serve to sharpen 
the conflict," he said when asked if China would veto UN 
Security Council sanctions. 
  "Exerting pressure is not helpful for carrying out dialogue, 
and we do not wish to see the issue referred to the UN Security 
Council," he said. 
  Wu did not respond to questions on whether Beijing and 
Pyongyang are presently holding consultations. 
  He said despite present difficulties, previous talks had 
progressed and he called on all sides to show patience. 

</TEXT>

