<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Li Peng Says Draft of `Resolution' on DPRK Issue Possible </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK2303015794 Seoul YONHAP in English 0131 GMT 23 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2303015794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 23 (YONHAP) -- Chinese Premier Li 
Peng said Tuesday that Beijing would draft a resolution stating 
its position on the North Korean nuclear dispute in case the UN 
Security Council takes up the issue. 
  At a press conference after the close of the National 
People's Congress meeting, Li reiterated that China believes the 
problem should be solved through dialogue and negotiation, 
rather than pressure, when asked to comment on recent 
developments. 
  He clearly reaffirmed China's opposition to the UN Security 
Council taking up the problem, because pressuring North Korea 
would not help the security of Northeast Asia but would only 
complicate matters and heighten tensions on the Korean peninsula. 
  He also stressed Beijing's desire for a nuclear-free Korean 
peninsula, noting that China as a signatory to the Nuclear 
Non-proliferation Treaty would never support an arms race. 
  Li hoped other permanent members of the UN Security Council 
would support China's resolution on the North Korean nuclear 
issue. 

</TEXT>

