<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Activist `Reasonably Confident' on Moves To Improve Rights </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK2403033694 Hong Kong SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST in English 
24 Mar 94 p 9 </F>

<F P=103> HK2403033694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By John Kohut in Beijing and Willy Wo-lap Lam] </F>
  [Text] Chinese officials have privately hinted at the 
possibility of more political prisoner releases and have also 
said that other differences with the U.S. over human rights 
could be resolved, according to Hong Kong-based human rights 
activist John Kamm. He said after meetings with State Council, 
Public Security and Supreme Court officials in Beijing, he was 
"reasonably confident there will be some moves in the next few 
weeks". 
  His talks with officials are the first indication that 
despite the tough human rights stance taken by China since the 
visit of American Secretary of State Warren Christopher this 
month, the Chinese leadership might be willing to make 
concessions quietly. 
  Mr Kamm said while Chinese officials repeated the line that 
they were prepared to lose the Most Favoured Nation (MFN) 
status, they were at pains to note prisoners who are sick, or 
who show a good attitude can be released in accordance with 
Chinese laws. They also said other human rights issues could be 
resolved with the United States through discussions based on 
mutual respect. 
  While this is far from a guarantee China will make the 
"significant progress" on human rights required by U.S. 
President Bill Clinton for MFN renewal, Mr Kamm said he was 
encouraged. "They're clearly committed to continuing the 
dialogue on human rights," Mr Kamm said. 
  As proof of that, he noted that all officials he requested 
to 
meet on this trip have agreed to speak to him "I think we'll see 
releases of sick prisoners and others," Mr Kamm said. But he 
added: "I was led to believe such moves could not be made 
immediately after the visit" of Mr Christopher. 
  In stating that Chinese law left room for prisoner releases 
based on humanitarian concerns or signs of good attitude, the 
officials tried to make clear that "we will no do these things 
because of American pressure, but be cause they are in 
accordance with the law," Mr Kamm said. No names or numbers of 
prisoners were discussed but Mr Kamm expects to go over a name 
list with Justice Ministry officials today. 
  Meanwhile, sources in the Chinese dissident community said 
the authorities had not decided whether to take "resolute 
action" against a number of activists who they believed would 
organise protest actions in the run-up to the fifth anniversary 
of the June 4, 1989, crackdown. 
  The sources said aside from the fear of fanning anti-MFN 
sentiment in the U.S. Congress, the authorities were worried 
that an excessive number of arrests would help galvanise the 
dissident movement. 
  In the past month, different groups have sent private 
letters 
to leaders demanding reforms including an end to the 
incarceration of citizens without recourse to the judicial 
process. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-3964 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drchi057_k_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-CHI-94-057 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  8 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

