<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> General </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhu Qizhen Opposes `Interference' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2603022494 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 1551 
GMT 25 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2603022494 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By reporter Zhang Youhao (1728 2589 3185)] </F>
  [Text] Paris, 25 Mar (XINHUA) -- Zhu Qizhen, head of the 
Chinese delegation attending the 91th Session of the 
Inter-Parliamentary Union [IPU] in Paris and also a vice 
chairman of the Foreign Affairs Committee of the Standing 
Committee of the Chinese National People's Congress, spoke today 
at a general debate of the session on the world's political, 
economic, and social situation. He emphatically pointed out: 
"China will hold dialogues about human rights on an equal 
footing; however, China strongly opposes any country's 
interference in other country's internal affairs under the 
pretext of human rights. Any pressure on other countries under 
the pretext of human rights and any statement or action which 
interferes in another country's internal affairs should be 
condemned." 
  Zhu Qizhen pointed out: "The Chinese Government has 
advocated 
on many occasions the establishment of a just and reasonable new 
international political and economic order with peace and 
stability on the basis of the five principles of peaceful 
coexistence and of the recognition of the diversity of the world 
and differences among various countries." 
  He said: The world is still turbulent and changeable, beset 
with many destabilizing factors, and is not peaceful. The peace 
and development so cherished by mankind face a serious challenge. 
  Touching on the establishment of a new international 
economic 
order, Zhu Qizhen pointed out: All countries have the right to 
independently choose their own social system, economic mode, and 
ways of development according to their own national situation. 
The developed countries should respect and show concern for the 
interests of developing countries, provide aid to developing 
countries without adding political conditions, strengthen 
dialogues between the North and South, and promote South-South 
Cooperation. 
  Zhu Qizhen briefly introduced China's great achievements 
over 
the past 15 years since the start of reform and opening up. He 
then said: "China is still a developing country with a low 
income. To develop into a mid-level developed country, it will 
require unremitting efforts for several generations. It is 
highly absurd for some people to consider China's economic 
development as a kind of `threat' and to disseminate the 
so-called `China threat.'" 
  When he finished his speech, the audience warmly applauded. 
Delegates from a number of countries came forward to shake hands 
with him and expressed their admiration and congratulations for 
his speech. 
  The current session opened on 21 March and is expected to 
end 
on 26 March. 

</TEXT>

