<F P=100> United States &amp; Canada </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Senator Baucus Comments on MFN Renewal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2603022894 Beijing XINHUA in English 0204 GMT 26 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2603022894 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Washington, March 25 (XINHUA) -- Most of the U.S. 
Senators now support renewal of China's most-favored-nation 
(MFN) trade status, the chairman of the U.S. Senate Finance 
Trade Subcommittee said here today. 
  Senator Max Baucus told reporters that issues of human 
rights 
and trade should not be linked because revoking China's MFN 
status would cause great harm to both the United States and 
China. 
  The linkage policy by the Clinton administration "is fraught 
with confrontation and has achieved minimal success," Baucus 
said. "No other country uses this blunderbuss approach," he 
added. 
  A clear majority in the Senate now supports severing link 
between China's human rights and trade and renewing China's MFN 
trade status, Baucus added. 

</TEXT>

