<H3> <TI>   Shanghai To Reform Commercial, Service Companies </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2603044094 Beijing XINHUA in English 0409 GMT 26 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2603044094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, March 26 (XINHUA) -- Shanghai has recently 
worked out a plan to launch a reform drive in commerce, 
featuring a shift to a modern enterprise system in its ten big 
commercial and service companies. 
  Meng Jianxiong, deputy major of this largest commercial city 
in China, told a local meeting that the drive will stress 
revising the existing management of state-owned property and 
forming a group of powerful corporations. 
  Topping the list of the city's ten main tasks is 
standardizing the management system of the ten nationally known 
commercial and service companies in the city, such as the 
Shanghai No. 1 Department Store and the Hualian Trade Mansion. 
  In addition, the city is to adopt a series of measures to 
promote the drive this year, including establishing ten large 
corporations through mergers and purchasing, improving its 19 
existing joint-stock companies and adding 10 more to the list. 
In addition, initial experiments in handling bankruptcies and 
mergers will be carried out, and 400 small-partnership 
commercial enterprises and 500 chain stores will be set up. 

</TEXT>

