<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kim Yong-sam Stresses Future-Oriented Economic Ties </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2803120394 Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service in Chinese 0914 
GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW2803120394 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA Domestic Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Chinese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, 28 Mar (XINHUA) -- Korean [ROK] President 
Kim Yong-sam, who is currently visiting Beijing, said here 
today: Korea and China should build future-oriented, 
complementary relations of economic cooperation. 
  Kim Yong-sam delivered a speech on Korean-Chinese economic 
relations and trade at a luncheon hosted by the China Council 
for the Promotion of International Trade, and the China Chamber 
of International Commerce. He said: Close cooperation between 
Korea and China can play its due role in promoting common 
prosperity in the two countries, as well as in stimulating the 
regional and world economies. 
  He said: Economic cooperation between the two countries 
should go beyond the stage of merely trading in materials and 
goods. The two countries should build future-oriented, 
complementary relations of cooperation by further expanding 
joint development and financing for new technology. 
  Kim Yong-sam expressed hope that Korean enterprises would 
actively participate in the Chinese market and seek common 
development with their Chinese counterparts. He said that 
Korean enterprises were capable of becoming good partners to 
their Chinese counterparts. 
  In his speech, Zheng Hongye, chairman of the China Council 
for the Promotion of International Trade and the China Chamber 
of International Commerce, expressed his belief that the 
president's current visit would definitely have a positive 
effect on promoting trade, as well as economic and technological 
cooperation and exchanges, between the two countries. 
  Before the luncheon, Li Lanqing, vice premier of the State 
Council, met Kim Yong-sam and his entourage at the Diaoyutai 
State Guesthouse. The two sides reviewed the development of 
economic relations and trade since their countries established 
diplomatic relations, unanimously maintaining that China and 
Korea should work harder to promote the further development of 
economic relations and trade. 

</TEXT>

