<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kim Yong-sam on ROK-PRC Trade Ties in Luncheon Address </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2803121694 Beijing XINHUA in English 1153 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2803121694 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 28 (XINHUA) -- Kim Yong-sam, 
visiting president of the Republic of Korea, said here today 
that the ROK and China should establish economic and trade 
relations which are mutually complementary and look towards the 
future. 
  He said that the close ROK-China economic and trade ties 
will 
not only contribute to the common prosperity of the two 
countries, but also to the active development of economies in 
Asia and in the world at large. 
  He made the statement in a luncheon in his honor hosted by 
the China Council for Promotion of International Trade (CCPIT) 
and China Chamber of International Commerce (CCIC). 
  Kim said that while continuing the two-way trade, the two 
countries should strengthen their joint development of new 
technology and establish more joint-ventures, in order to 
realize mutual complementary economic and trade relations with 
an eye to the future. 
  He expressed his hope that ROK enterprises should be more 
active in the Chinese market and develop along with their 
Chinese counterparts since there are factors conducive to their 
becoming good partners. 
  Zheng Hongye, president of both CCPIT and CCIC, said in his 
speech that he was confident that Kim's current visit will exert 
a positive influence on the promotion of bilateral trade and 
economic and technological cooperation. 
  Before the luncheon, Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing met 
with 
ROK President Kim and his party at the Diaoyutai State 
Guesthouse. 
  During the meeting, the two sides reviewed the development 
of 
bilateral economic and trade ties since the establishment of 
diplomatic relations. 
  They shared the view that the two governments should make 
greater efforts to promote these ties. 

</TEXT>

