<H3> <TI>   Beijing Opposes Pressure on DPRK, Military Exercises </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK2803062994 Hong Kong AFP in English 0616 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> HK2803062994 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 28 (AFP) -- China has refused to 
pressure North Korea into dropping its nuclear weapons program, 
saying it was against U.S.-South Korean military exercises and 
the deployment of Patriot missiles in the South. 
  "China is not in favour of any action or measures 
detrimental 
to the maintenance of peace and relaxation on the Korean 
peninsula, whether it was military exercise or deployment of 
missiles," said a Chinese foreign ministry spokesman told 
journalists. [sentence as received] 
  The spokesman, Shen Guofang, said China hoped the nuclear 
issue "shall be settled through patient and constructive talks 
between the parties directly concerned." 
  He made the remarks following a crucial meeting between 
South 
Korean President Kim Yong-sam and Communist Party General 
Secretary Jiang Zemin here Monday. 

</TEXT>

