<F P=100> Northeast Asia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Qian Qichen, ROK Foreign Minister Discuss Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2803134994 Beijing XINHUA in English 1330 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2803134994 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 28 (XINHUA) -- Chinese Vice-Premier 
and Foreign Minister Qian Qichen today conferred with visiting 
ROK (the Republic of Korea) Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu, on 
bilateral relations and international issues of common concern. 
  Referring to the nuclear issue on the Korean peninsula, Qian 
said there were twists and difficulties in the process of 
solving this problem. 
  However, he said it was imperative to see that the general 
trend was advancing, adding that one should be more calm and 
patient at a time when there appeared difficulty in the latest 
development of the situation. 
  Exerting pressure would only intensify contradictions, which 
would be no help in solving the problem, but make it 
complicated, he said. 
  Qian said the tense situation on the Korean peninsula would 
bring no benefit to the countries in this region. Therefore it 
was of vital importance to resume consultations among the four 
parties so as to solve the problem. 
  He said it was China's hope that the parties concerned would 
continue to make constructive efforts for peace to properly 
settle the nuclear issue on the peninsula. 
  Han said the ROK stands for patient dialogue and hoped for 
continuous efforts by the international community to settle the 
problem properly, especially through direct dialogue between the 
parties concerned. 
  But, he said, the window for dialogue is closed now and the 
issue has been raised at the United Nations Security Council, 
adding that the ROK still hoped to find a good solution to the 
issue. 
  This afternoon, Song Jian, China's state councillor and 
minister in charge of the State Science and Technology 
Commission, met with Kim Si-chung, the ROK minister of science 
and technology. The two exchanged views on the further growth 
of bilateral cooperation in science and technology. 
  Wang Zhongyu, Chinese minister in charge of the State 
Economic and Trade Commission, held talks with Kim Chol-su, the 
ROK minister of commerce, industry and resources, during which 
they explored ways and channels for expanding bilateral economic 
cooperation and trade. 

</TEXT>

