<F P=100> NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peng Peiyun Sees `Grim Prospects' for Population Situation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  HK2703050594 Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE in English 0256 GMT 
26 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> HK2703050594 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing ZHONGGUO XINWEN SHE </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Beijing, March 26 (CNS) -- State Councillor, Ms. 
Peng Peiyun, speaking at the second meeting of the board of 
directors of the China Population Welfare Foundation recently 
held here, said that though there had been a continuous drop in 
the birthrate in recent years, the population in the country was 
still facing grim prospects. 
  According to Ms. Peng, China is seeing over 20 million 
births 
annually with a net growth in the country's population of about 
14 million, causing the absolute number of births in the country 
to still remain very large and putting a heavy burden on the 
country. 
  Ms. Peng said that since there was a big gap between the 
state family planning policy and the desire for having children 
by farmers, the policy on family planning in the country was 
being carried out mainly through powerful executive measures and 
if there was any relaxation in this sector, the birth rate would 
soon deteriorate further. 
  The country has seen a serious problem in imbalance in the 
control of population growth in the country with 
children-bearing women in the 7 provinces and autonomous regions 
of Jiangxi, Guangxi, Yunnan, Guizhou, Tibet, Ningxia and 
Xinjiang to be in their peak birth state between 1997 and 2000. 
The country is, according to Ms. Peng, aso facing arduous tasks 
in the raising of the quality of population. The country now 
has 51.64 million disabled people, accounting for 2.4 percent of 
its total population, the disabled at the age of 0 to 14 years 
make up 3.66 percent of the total of the same age group, 65.96 
percent of whom are suffering from a mental problem. The rate 
of physical defects in newly-born babies is 1.3 percent of the 
total births in the country with Shanxi having a rate of 2 
percent, ranking the province first in the country. There are 
400 million people living in areas with an iodine-shortage 
problem, making up 40 percent o the total population facing the 
same problem in the world. Illiterate and semi-illiterate 
people in the country are now put at over 180 million with 
females accounting for 70 percent, posing a problem for the 
control of population growth and the raising of quality of 
people. 
  In addition, there are many problems in the population 
structure with boy births far exceeding those of girls. Owing 
to the drop in births and increasing life-span, China will enter 
peak aging society in the next century. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-4197 </DOCNO>
