<H3> <TI>   Pharmaceutical Industry Responding To Medical Needs </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2703134294 Beijing XINHUA in English 1328 GMT 27 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2703134294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Hangzhou, March 27 (XINHUA) -- China's 
pharmaceutical industry is taking its medicine: it is moving 
fast to increase its own development of new medicinal drugs. 
  This was made clear by an official at a conference dealing 
with the industry, which was just closed here in the capital of 
east China's Zhejiang Province. 
  Zhang Heyong, deputy director of the State Pharmaceutical 
Administration, said that the government's grants for research 
in the development of medicines had greatly increased. More 
than 400 such projects applied for approval last year, exceeding 
the total in past years. 
  China has started to adopt the modern enterprise system in 
this realm, to get away from the situation in which research 
institutions can only get funds through one channel -- 
government allocation. 
  The Xinhua Pharmaceutical Factory in Shandong Province and 
China Pharmaceutical University recently set up a corporation 
and a center for developing medicines, marking big progress in 
the field. 
  China now has 53 independent research and development 
institutions. But many problems still exist, such as 
overlapping functions and separation of research from production. 
  The central government is set to speed up the industry's 
readjustment, with stress on the establishment of advanced 
pharmacy centers. 
  It has made a success in Shanghai, which ranks 
pharmaceuticals among its pillar industries. The city now has 
four bio-engineering centers, with three others on the drawing 
board. 

</TEXT>

