<F P=101> Political &amp; Social </F>
<H3> <TI>   Returned Students Open Law Firm Offering Western Expertise </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW2803092094 Beijing XINHUA in English 0855 GMT 28 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2803092094 </F>
<F P=104>  Beijing XINHUA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Shanghai, March 28 (XINHUA) -- A new law firm run 
by Chinese students returned from overseas, believed to be the 
first of its kind in China, has commenced here recently. 
  The office is to provide legal services for both foreign 
business people who have had investment or wish to invest in 
China, and Chinese enterprises entering the world market. 
  It will also introduce Western law firm management 
expertise, 
said Cai Qing, director of the office, in his office in 
Shanghai's five-star Jinjiang Hotel. 
  Cai obtained a master's degree and then Ph.D in law in the 
United States and was qualified as a practising lawyer in 
Washington State before returning home, majoring in the laws of 
corporation, securities, investment and real estate. Cai's 
colleague Tang Yilin is also a registered practising lawyer in 
the United States. 
  The firm has five members who have settled down in the 
United 
States, and another four coming from the United States and 
Canada are expected to join the firm soon. 
  While mainly employing returned students, the firm is 
planning to recruit foreign lawyers, and it will also help send 
Chinese lawyers to engage in advanced training overseas. 
  Local experts believe there will be more such law firms in 
China along with the country's ongoing reform of the lawyer 
system and the nation's drive to build a socialist market 
economy. 
  China would regulate its lawyer system in line with 
international practice, Gan Jihua, vice-chairman of the 
Beijing-based All-China Lawyers Association, said. 

</TEXT>

